INSERT INTO `cultural_heritage_en` VALUES (320,'00200000','\nBulguksa, founded during the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign in Unified Silla (751), is a temple reflecting the spiritual world of Silla people who sought to embody the Pure Land, an ideal realm where past, present, and future Buddhas reside. According to the Samguk Yusa, Kim Dae-seong initiated the construction of Seokguram for his past parents and Bulguksa for his present parents. However, he couldn\'t complete Seokguram in his lifetime, and later, the state completed it to serve as a temple that would bring blessings to the country.\n\nDaebotap and Sakyamuni Pagoda (Three-story Stone Pagoda of Bulguksa, National Treasure) are the most representative stone pagodas in Korea, both standing at similar heights of 10.29m and 10.75m, respectively. Positioned facing each other in the courtyard between Daeungjeon Hall and Jahamun Gate, Daebotap is located to the east. Daebotap represents a special type of pagoda, while Sakyamuni Pagoda represents a standard type found in Korea. Placing these two pagodas in the same location was intended to visually depict the content of the Lotus Sutra, where the Buddha of the past, Daebul (Many Treasures Buddha), and the present Buddha, Sakyamuni, stand side by side during the latter\'s preaching to affirm the truth.\n\nExamining Sakyamuni Pagoda reveals a three-story structure atop a two-tiered pedestal, but Daebotap\'s number of tiers is challenging to count. The ten-armed cross-shaped pedestal features stone steps on all four sides, and the octagonal pagoda body with surrounding square railings is placed above it.\n\nThe construction of these pagodas is presumed to date back to the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign (751), coinciding with the founding of Bulguksa. These pagodas showcase a remarkable fusion of circles, squares, and octagons, maintaining uniformity in length, width, and thickness across different sections, highlighting the pinnacle of 8th-century Unified Silla artistry.\n\nUnfortunately, Daebotap carries the sorrowful legacy of the Japanese occupation. Around 1925, the Japanese dismantled and renovated the pagoda, leaving no records. The relics, cremated remains, and other artifacts inside the pagoda disappeared during this process. Additionally, of the four stone lions placed on the steps of the pedestal, three were looted by the Japanese, and despite efforts to recover them, their whereabouts remain unknown. Currently, only one stone lion remains.','11','Gyeongju city','Dabotap Pagoda of Bulguksa Temple, Gyeongju','card/5/BulguksaTempleDabotapPagoda.png','35.7899698186069','129.332267999295','Bulguksa Temple Dabotap Pagoda','慶州 佛國寺 多寶塔','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-00200000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/gosee_3d_motrip_ex16.mp4'),(321,'00210000','\nBulguksa, established in the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign in Unified Silla (751) by the patronage of Kim Dae-seong, embodies the spiritual world of Silla people who aimed to manifest the Pure Land, an ideal realm where Buddhas reside in the past, present, and future. According to the Samguk Yusa, Kim Dae-seong constructed Seokguram for his past parents and Bulguksa for his present parents. However, he couldn\'t complete Seokguram during his lifetime, and after his passing, the state completed it, designating it as a temple to bring blessings to the country.\n\nThe Three-story Stone Pagoda of Bulguksa and Daebotap Pagoda (National Treasure) in Gyeongju are both located in the courtyard to the east and west of the main hall, respectively, with the Three-story Stone Pagoda to the west. The original name of the pagoda is \'Sakyamuni Buddha\'s Permanent Residence and Dharma Setting Pagoda,\' commonly shortened to \'Sakyatap.\' Both pagodas represent the most iconic stone pagodas in Korea, standing at similar heights of 10.75m and 10.29m, respectively.\n\nBelieved to be constructed around the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign (751), the pagoda features three tiers erected on a two-tiered pedestal. Following the style of Gamsansa Three-story Stone Pagoda (National Treasure) and Goseonsa Three-story Stone Pagoda in Gyeongju, this pagoda is considered a superb work from the 8th-century Unified Silla era.\n\nTo support the entire weight of the pagoda, the two-tiered pedestal is intricately crafted, mimicking wooden construction by carving stones into pillar shapes at the corners of the upper and lower tiers. Similar pillars are also carved into the pagoda body, with the edges of the roof stones raised, creating a lively sensation as if the entire pagoda is soaring.\n\nRegrettably, in September 1966, the pagoda suffered damage at the hands of grave robbers. During repairs in December of the same year, a square space for enshrining the Buddha\'s relics was discovered in front of the pagoda\'s second-tier body stone. Various relic containers and artifacts, notably the \'Mugujeonggwang Dharani Sutra\' (National Treasure), were found. This sutra, made from paper mulberry wood, is the world\'s oldest woodblock print.\n\nThe pagoda\'s finial (top ornament) was restored in 1973, modeled after the finial of the Namwon Silsangsa East-West Three-story Stone Pagoda (Treasure) believed to have been lost before the 16th century. The surrounding stone-shaped capstones feature lotus patterns, interpreted as signifying a pure place for enshrining the Buddha\'s relics.\n\nThis pagoda is also known as the \'Muyeongtap\' (Shadowless Pagoda), featuring a poignant legend. It tells the story of Asadal, a stonemason who built Sakyatap in Baekje, and a Silla woman who came to the capital in search of her husband but tragically ended her life by throwing herself into a pond without meeting him.','11','Gyeongju city','The restored upper part of the three-story stone pagoda of Bulguksa Temple','card/5/BulguksaThreeStoryStonePagoda.png','35.7899677237892','129.331984595091','Bulguksa Three-story Stone Pagoda','慶州 佛國寺 三層石塔','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-00210000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/edu_kids_016.mp4'),(324,'00240000','Seokguram, initially called Seokbulsa, was constructed by Kim Dae-seong under the reign of King Gyeongdeok in the 10th year of the Shilla Dynasty (751) and completed in the 10th year of King Hyegong (774). During King Gyeongdeok\'s reign from 742 to 765, Shilla\'s Buddhist art flourished, giving rise to various cultural heritages such as Seokguram, Bulguksa, Dabotap Pagoda, Three-story Stone Pagoda, and Hwangnyongsa Temple.\n\nSituated on the midsection of Mt. Tohamsan, Seokguram was created artificially using white granite, with a main hall housing a central Buddha statue of Sakyamuni surrounded by 40 sculptures of bodhisattvas, disciples, and celestial beings. However, only 38 statues remain today.\n\nThe structure consists of a rectangular antechamber serving as the entrance and a circular main hall connected by a corridor acting as a passage. The architectural technique used 360 wide stones to intricately construct the ceiling of the circular main hall, showcasing unparalleled craftsmanship worldwide.\n\nThe antechamber, corresponding to the entrance of Seokguram, features four standing statues on each side. The corridor entrances exhibit Vajra warriors, and the narrow passage displays four directional guardians. Octagonal stone pillars are arranged on either side of the circular main hall entrance, where the central Buddha is positioned slightly to the rear. The walls of the main hall are adorned with celestial beings, bodhisattvas, arhats, and the exquisitely carved Eleven-faced Avalokitesvara on the circular wall behind the main Buddha statue.\n\nThe skilled craftsmanship and realistic depictions evident in the perfectly sculpted main Buddha, the beautifully carved Eleven-faced Avalokitesvara, the majestic Indra, and various bodhisattvas with unique expressions make every sculpture in Seokguram a masterpiece in East Asian Buddhist sculpture. The serene appearance of the main Buddha within the main hall enhances the mysterious atmosphere pervading Seokguram.\n\nA pinnacle of Shilla Buddhist art from its golden era, Seokguram seamlessly combines architecture, engineering, geometry, religion, and art. Designated as a National Treasure, Seokguram, along with Bulguksa Temple, achieved UNESCO World Heritage status in December 1995.\n\nDue to concerns about temperature and humidity affecting the interior, external viewing of Seokguram has been conducted through glass walls since 1976.','11','Gyeongju city','Seokgulam Grottoes seen from afar','card/5/SeokguramGrotto.png','35.794852','129.349242','Seokguram Grotto','慶州 石窟庵 石窟','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-00240000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/vod_sukgulam_01.mp4'),(325,'00250000','The stone monument erected in front of the shrine of King Taejong Muyeol, the 29th monarch of the Silla Dynasty, is called Taejong Muyeolwangreungbi. The monuments erected during the Unified Silla period were influenced by the Tang Dynasty in China, with the support stones taking the form of a turtle and the headstone depicting a dragon. Taejong Muyeolwangreungbi is considered the earliest example of this style.Inside the monument\'s frame, the body of the monument is missing, and only the headstone rests on the turtle-shaped support stone. The turtle is portrayed with its neck raised high, legs extended energetically forward, and a large hexagonal honeycomb pattern carved on its back. The monument base (biza) around the central hollow where the monument body would be placed is adorned with lotus decorations. On either side of the headstone, six dragons are intertwined, with three dragons each supporting a pearl in their mouths. In the center of the front side, the inscription reads \'Taejong Muyeol Daewangjibi,\' identifying the protagonist of the monument.Constructed in the first year of King Munmu\'s reign in 661 during the Unified Silla period, the monument features calligraphy by Kim Inmun, the second son of the renowned calligrapher and the martial King Muyeol. Known for its realistic expression and dynamic vitality, the monument conveys a strong impression as if the figures were alive, reflecting the progressive spirit of the Silla people who achieved the unification of the Three Kingdoms. Regarded as a masterpiece not only in Korea but also in East Asia, this work provides insights into the advanced state of stone carving techniques during that era.','11','Gyeongju city','King Taejong Muyeol’s tomb monument in Gyeongju seen from afar','card/5/TombstoneForKingTaejongMuyeol.png','35.8251335576631','129.188548279325','King Taejong Muyeol’s tombstone','慶州 太宗武烈王陵碑','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-00250000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(331,'00310000','This is an observatory from the Silla period that was used for observing celestial movements. It stands approximately 9 meters high, consisting of a cylindrical section resembling a liquor bottle placed on top of a pedestal-like base (Gidanbu, 基壇部) and crowned with a square-shaped upper section (Jeongsangbu, 井字形).\n\nThe cylindrical section is constructed with 27 layers of wedge-shaped stones, displaying a smooth and well-finished exterior, while the interior has irregularities due to protruding roots of stones and uneven surfaces. A window is located on the southeast side, with the lower part filled with stacked stones and the upper part open to the top. The eastern half of the upper section is blocked by flat stones, and the exposed end of a long stone, forming a square shape, extends to the outside. This design, observed in layers 19-20 and 25-26, suggests it was suitable for placing a ladder inside. According to ancient records, it was mentioned that \"a person can ascend through the center,\" indicating that a ladder could be placed on the outside, entering through the window, and ascending to the top to observe the sky.\n\nAstronomy was closely tied to agriculture, as it allowed for determining planting seasons based on celestial movements. Additionally, practices like astrology (Jeomseongsul, 占星術), which predicted national fortune based on observational results, were highly valued in ancient states, indicating a deep connection to politics. Consequently, astronomy garnered significant attention from early times, providing a favorable context for the construction of Cheomseongdae.\n\nBelieved to be built during the reign of Queen Seondeok (632–647), Cheomseongdae is considered the oldest observatory in East Asia, representing a valuable cultural heritage that reflects the advanced scientific knowledge of the time.','11','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Cheomseongdae','card/5/Cheomseongdae.png','35.834695848054','129.218993693668','Cheomseongdae','慶州 瞻星臺','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-00310000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/vod_signlang_05_03.mp4'),(350,'01880000','This is a gold crown from the Silla period discovered at Cheonmachong. Cheonmachong is a tomb designated as Tomb No. 155 in Gyeongju, and it gained its name after the excavation in 1973, during which a gold crown, bracelets, and many artifacts, including a heavenly horse painting (Cheonma-do), were found.\n\nThe gold crown, measuring 32.5 cm in height, is a typical Silla-style crown unearthed from Cheonmachong, worn by the person buried there.\n\nOn the wide band worn around the head, there are three lines of mountain-shaped patterns on the front and two lines of antler-shaped patterns on the back. The mountain patterns consist of four tiers, each ending in a flower-bud shape. The entire crown is adorned with circular gold plates and curved jade pieces, and meticulous details include twisted gold threads and closely connected gold plate decorations. Two hanging ornaments shaped like tree leaves are attached underneath.\n\nInside the gold crown, items needed for wearing or crafting a crown were discovered, all placed outside the inner part of the crown alongside other burial goods.','11','Gyeongju city','Cheonma Chonggeumgwan','card/5/CheonmachongGoldCrown.png','35.8293874259588','129.227912382125','Cheonmachong brass crown','天馬塚 金冠','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/11/kr-11-01880000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(2120,'00660000','A Seokbingo, or an ice storage facility, is a warehouse used for storing ice. The Seokbingo in question is located on the northern fortress wall within Gyeongju Banwolseong. It stretches from north to south and is positioned on top of the fortress wall.\n\nUpon entering through the entrance located on the southern side, visitors descend down stairs. As one progresses inside, the floor is inclined to allow water to flow, facilitating drainage. The roof is semi-circular, with three ventilation openings arranged to allow the exchange of air with the outside.\n\nAccording to the stone monument and the entrance imatdol, it is detailed in historical records that during the 14th year of King Yeongjo\'s reign in the Joseon Dynasty (1738), Chomyeonggyeom reconstructed the ice storage using stones, and four years later, it was relocated from the west to its current position. The Seokbingo is presumed to date from this period, and it is highly regarded as a masterpiece in terms of both scale and craftsmanship.','12','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Seokbinggo','card/5/Seokbinggo.png','35.8331434495042','129.22394548465','stone ice storage','慶州 石氷庫','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/12/kr-12-00660000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/gosee_3d_PER030303.mp4'),(2413,'09110000','The pagoda located about 150 meters northeast of Seokguram exhibits a distinctive structure with a two-tiered pedestal. The pedestal combines circular and octagonal shapes in a harmonious manner, and on top of it, a four-sided tower body is constructed in three tiers. The unique design of the pedestal lacks a clear explanation for its origin.\n\nOverall, this pagoda, believed to have been created in the late 8th century during the Unified Silla period, showcases a beautiful harmony of circles, squares, and octagons, along with a lively detailing technique.','12','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Seokguram Three-story Stone Pagoda','card/5/SeokguramThreeStoryStonePagoda.png','35.795394936334','129.350936449045','Seokguram Three-story Stone Pagoda','慶州 石窟庵 三層石塔','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/12/kr-12-09110000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(2514,'17440000','\n□ Location and Historical-Cultural Environment\nBulguksa is situated on the western slope of Mount Toham, the eastern peak of Donghak, facing south. The topography of Bulguksa is designed with the principle of \"northern high and southern low\" and \"eastern high and western low.\" The stone structures are harmoniously arranged, featuring stacked stones in a bracket-like structure. In the eastern sector, structures such as Jahamun, Daewoongjeon, and Museoljeon are arranged along the north-south axis to create a harmonious spatial layout.\n\nOn the east and west sides of Daewoongjeon, there are Ickrang (winged corridors), connecting to the east and west corridors, with Jwagyeongnu (left scripture pavilion) located at the east corner of the south corridor and Beomyeongnu (reflecting light pavilion) placed at the west corner. On the south side of Jahamun, Cheongungyo and Baegungyo bridges are constructed to facilitate entry and exit to Daewoongjeon.\n\n□ History and Architectural Features\n○ Historical Overview\nHistorical records about Bulguksa can be found in documents such as Samguk Yusa, Bulguksa Gogeum Changgi (Ancient and Modern Records of Bulguksa), and Daewoongjeon Jungchangdan Hwagigi (Record of Daewoongjeon Restoration). According to Samguk Yusa, it is presumed that Kim Dae-seong began the construction of Bulguksa in the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign (751, Xinmao) and completed it after the death of Daeseong in the 10th year of King Hyegong\'s reign (774, Gapin) on December 2.\n\nDaewoongjeon was reconstructed in the 18th year of King Sejong\'s reign (1436), with additional reconstructions in the 21st year of King Seongjong\'s reign (1490) and the 19th year of King Myeongjong\'s reign (1564). However, it was destroyed during the Japanese invasion in 1593. Subsequently, it was reconstructed in the 10th year of King Hyojong\'s reign (1659) and underwent repairs and replacements in various parts in subsequent years.\n\n○ Architectural Features\nDaewoongjeon has a rectangular plan of approximately 5 by 5 units with a slightly elongated east-west dimension, featuring a single-story, eight-sided hipped roof in the style of the late Joseon Dynasty. The exterior is decorated with lavish ornaments, including three-unit square flower-shaped doors in the central section, one-unit flower-shaped doors in the side sections, and intricate carvings of flowers and phoenix heads on the brackets and corners.\n\nThe building features a central high ceiling with a tiered structure. The eastern section of the central bay on the front side is occupied by Sabeomhwasal (Hall of Four Heavenly Kings), while the western section is blocked by a wall, and the rear section has a four-unit flower-shaped door. The side sections have double-wing doors, and the rear section has half-wing doors, with 10 of the 20 bays featuring open doors.\n\nThe foundation is made of square-cut stones with cornerstones and supporting stones, demonstrating the sophisticated construction techniques of the Unified Silla period. The central area of the foundation on all four sides has steps, and the triangular patterns on the side of the steps add an elegant touch.\n\nThe ceiling adopts a well structure, with a stepped central area.','12','Gyeongju city','Front of main hall of Bulguksa Temple, Gyeongju','card/5/BulguksaTempleMainHall.png','35.7901542005641','129.332064298536','Bulguksa Temple Main Hall','慶州 佛國寺 大雄殿','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/12/kr-12-17440000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(3236,'00180000','This is a stargazing pavilion located to the west of Anapji Pond, serving as the eastern palace where princes resided. It was used for banquets during important occasions or when receiving distinguished guests. It is also known for hosting a banquet in 931 AD, where King Gyeongsun invited Wang Geon to appeal for help during a crisis after the invasion by Gyeon Hwon.\n\nAfter the unification of the Three Kingdoms, in the 14th year of King Munmu\'s reign (674), Silla created a large pond, three islands in the middle of the pond, and twelve peaks to the north and east of the pond. It is said that beautiful flowers and trees were planted here, and rare birds and animals were raised. While the Samguk Sagi only mentions the Imhae Battle without any reference to Anapji, the Dongguk Yeoji Seungnam records, during the Joseon era, mention \"Imhaejeon is located to the west of Anapji.\" This led to the assumption that the current location is Anapji.\n\nDespite damages during the Japanese occupation, including the construction of a railway passing through the area, 26 building sites, including a royal banquet hall, were identified around the pond near the Imhaejeon site. Three out of five building sites believed to be Silla structures, including the one presumed to be Imhaejeon, have been restored along with Anapji.\n\nNumerous artifacts were unearthed, such as bricks with decorative patterns, bearing the inscription \"Jo-ro 2nd year (680),\" supporting the assertion that Imhaejeon was built during King Munmu\'s reign. Many utensils, including serving dishes, were discovered, suggesting practical usage in daily life, unlike artifacts found in Silla tombs.\n\nWhile Imhaejeon was a building within the royal palace, it played a significant role, and Anapji remains a representative archaeological site of Silla\'s artificial ponds.','13','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Donggung Palace and Wolji Pond','card/5/DonggungPalaceAndWoljiPond.png','35.83471758976','129.226486463902','Donggung Palace and Wolji Pond','慶州 東宮 月池','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-00180000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/gosee_vdo_OLD020012.mp4'),(3238,'00200000','The tomb of King Muyeol (reigned 654–661), the 29th monarch of the Silla Dynasty, is situated on the eastern hillside of Seondo Mountain, west of downtown Gyeongju. It is one of the five large tombs in the area, positioned at the lowest level.\n\nKing Muyeol succeeded Queen Jindeok and was the first king from a true-bone (jin-gol) lineage, with his birth name being Kim Chun-chu. Renowned for his alliance with the Tang Dynasty and the conquest of Baekje, he laid the foundation for the unification of the Three Kingdoms. According to \"Samguk Sagi,\" he ascended the throne in 661 and passed away after just eight years of rule in June 661. His posthumous title, Shihou (諡號), is Muyeol (武烈), and his temple name is Taejong (太宗). It is recorded that he was buried to the north of Yeongneungsa Temple.\n\nAlthough excavation surveys have not been conducted, it is presumed to be a cave-style tomb with a gourd-shaped stone chamber. Compared to other tombs from the Unified Silla period, its mound decoration is relatively simple, with natural stones forming the perimeter around the tomb. To the northeast of the tomb stands the Gyeongju Taejong Muyeolwangreungbi (National Treasure).\n\nThe Muyeolwangreung Tomb is a significant burial site among Silla\'s royal tombs, uniquely identifying the tomb owner. The area was renovated in 1972-1973 for preservation and is well-maintained to this day.','13','Gyeongju city','Panoramic view of King Muyeol’s tomb in Gyeongju','card/5/RoyalTombOfKingTaejongMuyeol.png','35.8251520779403','129.187876707128','King Muyeol\'s tomb','慶州 武烈王陵','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-00200000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/gosee_vdo_flv_20100015.mp4'),(3239,'00210000','Located to the east of Mount Songhwa in Gyeongju, this is the tomb of Kim Yushin, a Silla general. Kim Yushin (595–673) played a central role in the unification of the Three Kingdoms. He established a political foundation by forming a blood relationship with Kim Chun-chu (later King Taejong Muyeol) and achieved significant success in various battles and uprisings. In 660, he became the leader of the nobility and played a key role in the downfall of Baekje. In 668, he became the Supreme Commander of the Silla military, bringing about the demise of Goguryeo and thwarting Tang Dynasty invasions, solidifying his position as a crucial figure in the unification of the Silla Three Kingdoms. The tomb has a large diameter of 30 meters, and its mound has a rounded shape. Below the mound, perimeter stones are arranged, surrounded by stone pillars. The perimeter stones alternate between those without carvings and those with carvings of the 12 zodiac animals. The zodiac figures are depicted wearing plain clothes, holding weapons, with human bodies and animal-shaped heads. Though the carvings are shallow, they exhibit a highly sophisticated skill. The practice of carving zodiac figures on the perimeter stones around tombs emerged in Unified Silla after the era of King Seongdeok, as evidenced by the tombs surrounding this one. According to the \"Samguk Yusa,\" King Heungdeok posthumously honored Kim Yushin as King Heungmu, and the tomb was adorned with royal rites. In \"Samguk Sagi,\" it is reported that when Kim Yushin passed away, King Munmu conducted a proper funeral and erected a memorial monument to honor his virtues. However, the current monument remains from the one established during the Joseon Dynasty by Gyeongju Buyun, titled \"Silla Taedae-gakgan Kim Yushinmyo,\" as the original monument was not preserved.','13','Gyeongju city','Cemetery view','card/5/RoyalTombOfKingTaejongMuyeol.png','35.8451408198327','129.191472432783','Tomb of Kim Yu-shin','慶州 金庾信墓','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-00210000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(3325,'04570000','\nChunyanggyo and Woljeonggyo in Gyeongju are currently situated to the west of the National Gyeongju Museum and on the south bank of the Gyocheon Stream in Gyeochon Hanok Village. According to records, in the 19th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign (760) as documented in the \"Samguk Sagi,\" two bridges named \"Woljeong\" and \"Chunyang\" were constructed over the southern Gyocheon Stream in the palace.\nBased on excavation findings, Chunyanggyo site consists of piers on both sides, wing walls, and three boat-shaped piers on the riverbed. Using this information, it is estimated that the dimensions of the bridge were approximately 55m in length, 5m in height, and 12m in width of the bridge deck.\nThe Woljeonggyo site is composed of piers on both sides, wing walls, and four boat-shaped piers, suggesting a bridge length of about 60m. Additionally, the discovery of charred wood and tile fragments between the piers indicates a structure resembling a pavilion (nugak) with a tiled roof on the bridge deck.\nBased on archaeological research and excavation results, Woljeonggyo has been reconstructed with pavilions on both sides of the bridge and a bridge deck in the present form from 2008 to 2018.\nChunyanggyo and Woljeonggyo, designated as national treasures, serve as archaeological evidence of the structure and construction technology of bridges during the Unified Silla period. These bridges likely played a crucial role in connecting the northern and southern parts of Wolseong, serving as essential transportation routes during that era.','13','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Chunyang Bridge and Woljeong Bridge-Woljeong Bridge Bridge Stone Pond','card/5/WoljeonggyoBridge.png','35.829237247077','129.221844810706','Chunyanggyoji and Woljeonggyoji','慶州 春陽橋址 月精橋址','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-04570000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/'),(3331,'05020000','\nBulguksa, located on Mount Toham in Gyeongju, was initiated by Kim Dae-seong, the governor of the time, in the 10th year of King Gyeongdeok\'s reign (751) and completed in the 10th year of King Hyegong\'s reign (774). However, during the Japanese invasion in the 26th year of King Seonjo\'s reign (1593), most of the buildings were destroyed by fire.\n\nFollowing the invasion, only a few structures such as Geukrakjeon, Jahamun, and Beomyeongru continued the legacy. Through excavation and restoration from 1969 to 1973, Bulguksa was revived to its current state.\n\nWithin the grounds, designated as national treasures, are the Dabotap and the three-story stone pagoda known as Seokgatap, along with Cheongungyo and Baegungyo bridges leading to Jahamun, and Yeonhwa and Chilbo bridges leading to Geukrakjeon. These cultural heritage sites showcase the exceptional stone craftsmanship of the Silla people.\n\nAdditionally, the treasures housed in the Birojeon, including the Gilt-bronze Buddha Triad and the Gilt-bronze Amitabha Buddha Triad in Geukrakjeon, reflect the splendid Buddhist culture of that era. Recognizing these values, Bulguksa, along with Seokguram, was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in December 1995.','13','Gyeongju city','Gyeongju Bulguksa Temple','card/5/BulguksaTemple.png','35.79015651','129.332056','Bulguksa Temple','慶州 佛國寺','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-05020000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/gosee_vdo_PEO040012.mp4'),(18175,'05480000','\"Bunhwangsa Temple Site\" is the location where the representative Silla temple, \'Bunhwangsa,\' once stood. According to the records of \"Samguk Yusa\" and \"Samguk Sagi,\" Bunhwangsa Temple was established in the third year of King Seondeok\'s reign (634). It holds historical significance as a venerable temple where the monks Jajang and Wonhyo propagated Buddhism during its founding years.\n\nExcavation surveys were conducted from 1990 to 2014, revealing the present and external areas of the site. It was discovered that the temple was originally constructed in the unique architectural style called \'Iltaebop Samgeumdangshik Garam,\' with a central pagoda surrounded by three halls facing east, west, and north. After three reconstructions, the current structure, Bogwangjeon Hall, was built in the first year of King Gwanghae\'s reign in 1609.\n\n\'Iltaebop Samgeumdangshik Garam\': Architectural style in which a pagoda is surrounded by three halls facing east, west, and north.\nBunhwangsa was one of the seven temples (Chilcheogaram) constructed in the pre-unification Silla capital of Gyeongju, along with Hwangnyongsa and Heungnyunsa. The site is home to the National Treasure \"Gyeongju Bunhwangsa Pagoda Stone Monument.\" Through extensive and systematic excavations, the temple\'s layout and changes in the site, as well as much of the historical area, have been revealed, making it an archaeological site of significant historical and academic value.\n\nChilcheogaram (Seven-Temple Complex): One of the Buddhist theories in Silla, indicating seven temple complexes in Gyeongju, including present-day Heungnyunsa, Yeongheungsa, Hwangnyongsa, Bunhwangsa, Yeongmyosa, Cheonwangsa, and Dammulsa.','13','Gyeongju city','Panoramic view of Bunhwangsa Temple Site (Gyeongju National Research Institute of Cultural Heritage)','card/5/BunhwangsaTemple.png','35.8408943467962','129.233647482743','Bunhwangsa Temple Site','慶州 芬皇寺址','http://116.67.83.213/media/voice/krVoice/13/kr-13-05480000-37.mp3','Gyeongbuk','http://116.67.83.213/webdata/file_data/media_data/videos/');
